My setup:
- 17 L saddle bag
- 3.5 L frame bag
- 1x12 L, 1x15 L compression bag
- 0.75 L top tube bag
- snack pouch
- 0 degree sleeping bag
- 2 person tent
- sleeping pad
- 1 tube, chain breaker, quick link, cleat bolts, hockey tape, small piece of chain, 2 strings

Clothes went into the 12 L compression bag in my saddle bag which also held the pads, pillow, and rain coat. The saddle bag also had a bungie strap that was ultra useful for holding stuff like brie cheese, loaf of bread, sandwiches, tofu, and drying swim clothes mid ride.

Tools, lights and cables, utensils, sunscreen, and laundry string went into the frame pack. We used the string to hang and air out our clothes overnight.

The tent and fly went into my 15 L compression bag along with my sleeping bag. We tied that bag to the aero bars with some string. 

The top tube bag held a 20,000 mAh battery, my phone, and cards (debit, cc, id, health card). The battery lasted us 4 days charging a Wahoo Element Bolt GPS, 2 phones, a headlamp, a 650 lumen light, and a 500 lumen light. The battery was down to 3% by the end of the trip. 

The snack pouch held a tube that didn't fit anywhere else and a bunch of coconut almond date snacks. I also put a bottle of apple juice in it once. 

The weather couldn't have been better - it didn't rain and was never too hot. I think we would have been fine without a 15 L dry sack we brought and my rain coat but it did help keep the mosquitos out and keep me warm with a thin fleece sweater.

Sleeping bag was always warm enough too. 

Notes on body pain: the muscles were completely fine. It was the contact points that hurt. By the end of day 2 the bottoms of my feet were on fire so insoles or better fitting shoes would have been helpful. And chamois butter?

column3: WCC Saturday Gravel ft. Fun trails and many unfortunate mishaps
column5: Testing this Maurten thing out. Seems to work better than maple syrup, has a milder flavour, doesn't leave a sticky feeling in your mouth. Weird texture with the tiny microbeads but I kinda like that.

Gravel, singletrack, and trail centuries hit a little different... Woke up at 3 am to meet up with a group of WCC+1 Bateman's bikepackers at their campsite outside Paris around 7 am. A couple of hours of gravel, singletrack, sandy paths, an old bridge once used for a railway line and a few hidden walk-only bridges later we were in Ayr with 140 km to go. 

It started to drizzle as we were riding on the outskirt of someone's farm field into a forest, Kevin got a flat, and then it really started to rain. The bikepackers kept going but it was all part of the fun as Hyrum, Joel, and I chased them down. The rain and cloud cover kept the temperature comfortable. 

Quote of the day: "hey are we going over there? It's sunny there". "Ya in like 3-4 hours". But the day went by quickly riding with people and the sun came out in the home stretch. Super fun ride overall. Would definitely do it again.



Nutrition notes: 800kcal maurten consumed in 5x500ml evenly spaced, 1 bottle nuun at 145 km because it wasn't hot, starbucks coffee cold drink in Ayr, 0.5 bagel at hour 1, 0.5 bagel at hour 2, 2 timmies cinnamon raisin cookies at Paris campground, 1 clif bar at that bridge, 2 junior mcchicken 1 doughnut 1 salty fry in New Hamburg, some cheese curds. Eat frequently in steady small manageable portions!

Spent 20 minutes wondering why the pace is so brutal. Then I found out the guy at the front is the current US national champion. Luckily we eased up.
Finished in the dark and below 10 degrees.
No to aero bars, yes to bibs

Rode out to Mono Hills to meet Oliver and Kian on the last day of their BT 700. Some fun trails from Glen Haffy to the rail trail then I let Oliver time trial with his aero bars out front while I DJ-ed behind him. Rode through Forks of the Credit park, found some interesting tree covered ATV trails I didn't know existed and a way to get out of the G2G on the other side of the bridge. Ended with a beautiful sunset again.

Looks like I finally found a bike fit, bib shorts, and shoes/insoles that let me ride all day with minor aches. Also very happy that I still had some snap and sustain power at the end... Those ridiculous TrainerRoad intervals work. But maybe that was partly the food calling.

column5: Successful day. Vicious headwind for the last 90 km but finished feeling good with daylight to spare, had some crepes, and found a good place to set up the tent.

The smoked trout crepe in Midland is amazing. Met lots of nice people today. One group was riding from Owen Sound to Ottawa. The section near Penetanguishene and Midland is a lot of fun: steep short up downs with bridges over creeks at the bottoms. Found a couple old forts from the settling period. Also so many murals in Midland portraying life when the railroads were booming.
I think 4 or 5 hours of 20 kph headwind today... But that concludes part 1 of checking out the remnants of a vast rail network. This was a good month for cycling.

column3: Janky and Sandy Day 2 on the COLT
column5:
WOW. Such interesting terrain. But 38mm tubeless low pressure is the minimum rideable setup around here üòÖ. Steep chunky rock and sand hills with the Canadian shield right on the "road". Would love to spend more time exploring! We saw some people with big mountain bike 2.3 or 2.4 knobbies. But they were taking the Hastings Heritage all the way to Bancroft. The portion after the crown land gets way sandier, hence the unmaintained detours which are just amazing. Finished the ride at Thom and Sue's around a fire listening to stories about some of the riding here.

Biggest week and 4 week rolling average ever by time and distance ‚úÖ
